<p><img width="406" height="232" src="https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/tiling-shell-bw-406x232.jpg" class="attachment-post-list size-post-list wp-post-image" alt="" decoding="async" srcset="https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/tiling-shell-bw-406x232.jpg 406w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/tiling-shell-bw-300x172.jpg 300w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/tiling-shell-bw-840x480.jpg 840w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/tiling-shell-bw-350x200.jpg 350w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/tiling-shell-bw-768x440.jpg 768w , https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/tiling-shell-bw.jpg 1440w " sizes="(max-width: 406px) 100vw, 406px" />If you&#8217;ve tried the Tiling Shell GNOME extension you&#8217;ll know how easy it makes it to tile application windows in GNOME Shell, from simple to more complex. The latest update, which began rolling out through the GNOME Extensions website this weekend, adds yet another intuitive way to tile windows as you work. First it provided a slide-in Windows 11-style Snap Assistant on to which you drop windows to tile them accordingly. Next, it added keyboard shortcuts to support tiling windows without using a mouse. More recently, edge-tiling was introduced. And you can activate an on-screen drop-zone by moving a window [&#8230;]</p>
